Translated_Notes: The 4th-5th grade was at an outdoor school in the area near Ospevika Cemetery. We found both empty shells and living individuals. The sign, together with another class, found many dead shells on the same beach in June 2010. The photo could not be uploaded today. . Validation status: Approved Documented

Translated_Notes: Completed structured inspection, 2nd year. Thousands of shells this year too, some flat oysters. Debris in several bonfires on land as well as picking people at the site indicate that the resource is increasingly being exploited. Own detailed reporting to the Norwegian Environment Agency. Validation status: Approved Documented

Notes: Vi plukket opp ca 450 små/unge stillehavsøsters fra mudderflatene som ligger som et langt belte langs siden av Askerøya i Selviksund. Det er blitt enorme mengder stillehavsøsters her siden i fjor. Det er så kaldt i vannet så vi orker ikke bade for å ta opp de som er under vann. Her trengs det innsats fra mange mennesker med tykke våtdrakter og neoprensko.  Vi smasha ca 500 stillehavsøsters som satt fast på steiner på mudderbunne langs kanten av Askerøya. Vi smasha også ca 20 voksnne stillehavsøs
Translated_Notes: We picked up about 450 small/young Pacific oysters from the mud surfaces located as a long belt along the side of Askerøya in Selviksund. There have been huge numbers of Pacific oysters here since last year. It's so cold in the water so we can't take bathers to pick up those who are underwater. Many people with thick wetsuits and neoprene shoes are needed here. We smashed about 500 Pacific oysters that were stuck on rocks on mud bottom along the edge of Askerøya. We also smashed about 20 waxy Pacific esophes

Notes: Beate, Dorte Meilvan og Ingunn Langenyr smashet ca 1030 stillehavsøsters i flere størrelser (mange snå, unge) på mudderflatene langs Askerøya i Selviksund. De har nå spredd seg i store mengder oppover langs denne siden, - DET TRENGS STOR INNSATS FRA MANGE FOLK FOR Å FJERNE RESTEN. Validationstatus: Approved Documented
Translated_Notes: Beate, Dorte Meilvan and Ingunn Langenyr smashed about 1030 Pacific oysters in several sizes (many weird, young) on the mud surfaces along Askerøya in Selviksund. They have now spread in large numbers upwards along this side, - IT TAKES a LOT OF EFFORT FROM A LOT OF PEOPLE TO REMOVE THE REST. Validation status: Approved Documented

Notes: Beate (jeg) padlet kajak inn i den grunne lille Spekebukta sammen med Dorte Meilvang, der plukket vi opp 34 løstliggende stillehavsøsters og tok med til brygga ved hytta og smashet dem, matet måkene med dem. Notes: Non-indigenous species Invasion year: 2007 (North Sea) In the southern part (region V) Pacific oyster was found at 6 out of 25 sites, with the most southerly location close to Falkenberg. In the northern part of the west coast of Sweden (region VI) Pacific oyster was found at 36 out of 43 investigated sites. The highest abundances were also found in the northern region.  Population status: Common (Moderate level of certainty) Despite fluctuations due to high winter mortality the species is common in large part of the Skagerak. Pathway: Natural spread from neighboring countries Vector: (Highly likely) Water currents
